<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDEPENDENT Newspapers, the Irish newspaper and publishing group, yesterday
reported a 20 per cent drop in pre-tax profits, from IPounds 9.99m to
IPounds 7.97m (Pounds 7.45m), for the year to December 27.
Turnover of the group's worldwide operations was marginally up at IPounds
155.8m (IPounds 154.9m). Exceptional costs amounting to IPounds 3.37m
related to redundancies and the unsuccessful bid for Australia's John
Fairfax newspaper group accentuated the profits fall from the company's
overseas markets.
However, Mr Liam Healy, group chief executive, said that growth in
advertising and circulation revenues in the home market helped the domestic
operations increase profitability. Turnover in Ireland totalled IPounds
120m, giving operating profits of IPounds 13.5m. The overseas arms made
IPounds 2.6m on turnover of IPounds 35m.
Net interest charges were halved to IPounds 2.53m (IPounds 5.11m) after debt
was reduced to IPounds 8.8m (IPounds 47.6m) at the year-end. The cut in debt
was largely due to the raising last April of IPounds 30m in a convertible
capital bond and the repayment of an ADollars 20m loan, relating to the
investment in Australian Provincial Newspapers.
Earnings per share declined to 18.8p (23.77p). A final dividend of 9p (8.5p)
is recommended, for a total of 14p (13p).
Following the failure of its Fairfax bid, Independent is now interested in
taking a stake in Mirror Group Newspapers. 'If shares were put up for sale
by the administrator, we would take a look,' said Mr Healy.
