<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / UK groups plan US placements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE more UK companies are poised to raise finance in the US private
placement market this week, adding to the growing number of overseas
corporations raising long-term debt funding from US institutional investors.
The deals come at a time of few public Eurobond offerings or large
syndicated bank borrowings by UK companies.
The proceeds of many of the placements are being used to repay outstanding
short-term bank debt.
Bankers in New York said Pilkington, the glass-maker, was considering a
Dollars 200m (Pounds 116m) placement of bonds with US institut- ional
investors. The securities will have a 15-year maturity.
Tate &amp; Lyle, the foods group, is placing Dollars 50m seven-year bonds and
Senior Engineering is raising Dollars 30m, also over 15 years.
Last week, Lucas Industries raised Dollars 100m 12-year finance from a group
of five US investors and Harrisons &amp; Crosfield raised Dollars 100m 10-year
and 12-year funding. The deals were arranged by Wertheim Schroder and
Barclay's de Zoete Wedd, respectively.
Lucas used the proceeds of its placement to repay all but Dollars 30m
outstanding commercial paper borrowings in the US market.
Mr David Creed, Tate &amp; Lyle treasurer, said the company hoped to use the
proceeds of a US private placement to refinance a maturing Dollars 100m
Eurobond and repay bank borrowings in the US. However, he said firm details
of the placement had not been fixed.
The companies are keen to lock into long-term committed funding while banks
are mostly unwilling to make unsecured loans of more than five years.
With the economic outlook uncertain, banks do not want to take on exposure
to corporate credit risk for long periods.
The public bond markets are equally wary of corporate credit risk.
Large companies can still raise funding at attractive rates in the Eurobond
market, but only up to 10-years maturity.
The US private placement market amounted to Dollars 160bn last year, but
overseas companies accounted for only between 5 per cent and 10 per cent of
the total raised.
</TEXT>
