FT  09 APR 92 / Charity's links with Natural Law party probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHARITY Commission has launched a preliminary investigation into the
activities of a UK-based charity because of its connections to a newly
founded political party that has been actively campaigning for votes in
today's general election.
It emerged yesterday that the commission has approached the registered
charity the World Government for the Age of Enlightenment of Great Britain
for information about its links with the Natural Law party, which is
fielding 310 candidates.
The commission is trying to establish whether the charity may be in breach
of regulations by straying too far into the field of political activity.
Officials for the commission say the decision to conduct a preliminary
investigation was made after the publication of advertisements in the
national media and 'representations' from unnamed members of the public.
They focus on full-page advertisements placed on separate days by the
charity and by the Natural Law party.
The charity is the local branch of a worldwide organisation focused on the
teachings of the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi, which has its headquarters at
Vlodrop in the Netherlands.
Funding for the Natural Law party advertisement came from the Association of
the International World Plan Executive Council (AIWC), also based in the
Netherlands, which is part of the Maharishi's international organisation.
Mr Peter Warburton, a spokesman for the Natural Law party, said that many of
the candidates of the party had practised the Transcendental Meditation
programme founded by the Maharishi, but denied that the campaign was funded
by the charity.
He said that the NLP had paid for its advertisment with a loan from the AIWC
and that the money 'will be repaid'.
He described the AIWC as an international foundation set up to help to fund
natural law projects around the world. The party had also received financial
support at a national level from 'well-wishers who do not want their names
revealed'.
The NLP says it has spent Pounds 1m on its campaign since officially
launching itself soon after the campaign started.
The candidates for the NLP include Mr Leslie Davis and Mr Roger Chalmers,
two doctors who were struck off the register last October after being found
guilty of serious professional misconduct by the General Medical Council.
</TEXT>
