<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / World Trade News: Norway may get sharp boost in gas payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEVERAL European buyers of natural gas from Norway's giant Troll field have
agreed to a novel adjustment in the terms of their purchase contracts which
could increase significantly sales revenue for Europe's biggest gas
supplier.
Norway this year will export more than 28bn cubic metres (bcm) of gas to
France, Germany, Holland, and Belgium. However, exports will expand to
around 40 bcm of gas in 1994 under the Troll supply agreement.
Statoil, the Norwegian state oil company, leads the consortium which sells
natural gas on Norway's behalf. Under a new clause in the Troll supply
contract - a so-called price review clause - both the buyer or seller may
demand prices per cubic metre of gas be renegotiated at any given point in
time to better reflect prevailing market conditions.
European demand for natural gas has grown fast since the Troll sales
contract was agreed in 1986 and the price review clause works to the
advantage of Norway which is coming under increased pressure to meet rising
demand.
For example, for each NKr0.01 per cubic metre increase in the sales price of
the gas, Norway's sales revenue could rise by some NKr400m annually if
Norway deemed that market conditions had changed since the original price
was agreed in 1986.
By the year 2010 supplies from the Troll field alone could peak at up to 50
bcm annually. This could mean a massive increase in revenue for Norway.
There are 'fixed criteria' under which market conditions can by definition
be considered to have changed, but these details are known only to the
sellers and buyers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
