<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow falls 62 points amid sell
programs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCK prices plunged across the board yesterday as nervousness about the
decline in Tokyo markets coupled with Wall Street computerised sell programs
wiped more than 50 points off the Dow Jones Industrial Average, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
By the close the Dow was down 61.94 at 3,213.55. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500
finished 7.53 weaker at 398.06, while the Nasdaq composite index of
over-the-counter stocks dropped 14.68 to 581.61. Turnover on the New York SE
amounted to 205m shares, while falls outnumbered rises by more than
three-to-one.
In the absence of fresh economic news, and lacking a firm direction from
bonds, the newfound confidence about the economic and earnings outlook that
fuelled Monday's rise vanished yesterday. Some analysts said they detected
the first signs of genuine unease among investors about the effect on US
markets of the heavy losses in Japanese equities. The trigger for the sudden
sell-off, however, was a big computerised sell program mid-afternoon, which
single-handedly wiped 20 points off the Dow average.
One observer said that he believed the program involved a strategic shift of
assets out of stocks and into other forms of investments. The program was
swiftly followed by several others, and amid a lack of buyers, prices
dropped sharply in the final 1 1/2 hours.
One of the few big stocks to buck the trend was General Motors, which
climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 38 in turnover of almost 3m shares. Trading
was delayed at the opening due to an order imbalance on the buy side as
investors responded favourably to news of a 'mini coup' in GM's boardroom.
Mr Robert Stempel, GM group chairman, was ousted from his position as head
of the board's key policy-making executive committee, being replaced by an
outside director.
Airline shares, already undermined by higher oil prices and fears of a fresh
price-cutting war among big carriers, were hit particularly hard. UAL
weakened Dollars 10 1/4 to Dollars 129 1/2 , Delta Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars
58 7/8 , AMR Dollars 4 1/4 to Dollars 67 1/2 and USAir Dollars 3/4 to
Dollars 16 1/8 .
Oil issues, which played a big part in Monday's advance, were weaker. Texaco
lost Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 59 3/4 , Occidental Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 18
7/8 , BP ADR's Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 52 1/4 , Chevron Dollars 2 1/8 to
Dollars 65 1/4 and Exxon Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 56 5/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Right Management plunged Dollars 9 1/2 to Dollars 8
after the company estimated first-quarter earnings would be between 8 and 13
cents a share, down sharply from 36 cents in the same quarter a year ago.
Canada
TORONTO plummeted nearly 50 points or 1.5 per cent, its sharpest drop for 1
1/2 years. Dealers said players have been backing away from the market for
the past month and listless volumes have exaggerated the swings in the
market.
Nervousness over rising inflation and fears the trend towards lower interest
rates has come to an end may have contributed to the sharp losses, some
added. The market is waiting for the US producer and consumer price indices
for March to be released tomorrow and Friday respectively.
The composite index dropped 49.3 to 3,336.6. Declines led advances by 388 to
195 on volume of 25.5m shares.
Confirmation that Olympia &amp; York missed a payment of USDollars 62m on March
25 weakened bank shares, already reeling from the property giant's cash flow
troubles.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
