<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / UK Company News: Row flares over rise in charge for debit
card
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROW between banks and retailers over charges for debit and credit cards
flared yesterday when Sir Ian MacLaurin declared he was 'very, very unhappy'
about proposed increases.
He used stronger language in saying that the British Retail Association was
aiming to take a firm line in negotiations with the banks.
Mr David Malpas said the banks had behaved disgracefully. The group had
invested up to Pounds 30m in the equipment to take debit cards, he said,
because the banks had decided it would be easier to handle transactions
electronically rather than using cheques.
When customers pay by debit card the money is electronically transferred
from their bank account to the retailer's account.
Mr Malpas said the banks were now 'hiking up charges to an unsupportable
level'. Banks and retailers had agreed that the charge for debit cards would
be no more than for cheque processing, about 4p to 5p a transaction across
the industry. The banks were looking to charge retailers twice that for
handling a transaction on Switch, the electronic-only debit card system, he
said.
Switch accused the retailers of wanting a Rolls Royce service for the cost
of a Mini.
'Switch was costly to develop, costing over Pounds 100m to set up. We did
tell many of the retailers that the prices we offered during the start up
period were initial pricing but they seem to have been taken by surprise
that rates have finally had to go up,' Mr Tim Green, managing director of
Switch, the largest UK debit card scheme, said.
Mr Green conceded that the charges for Switch were now higher than those for
cheques.
'We admit that at present Switch's charges are a few pence more than the
price of cheque collection. But it is too good a service for the retailers
to pass over.'
Barclays said that the flat charge on each Visa debit card transaction went
up from 10.5p to 12p two months ago, though it was still well below the
17.5p charged in 1987 when the card was launched.
Tesco said that the banks had also unilaterally demanded an increase in fees
for credit card transactions.
Mr Malpas said that about 40 per cent of Tesco's sales were paid for by
credit or debit cards. He said customers liked using the debit cards and
their usage had grown rapidly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-14053</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDHA7AE7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920408
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / O&amp;Y hits hurdle in plan to pay debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK, the debt- burdened property developer, is struggling to find
a buyer for a 36-storey Toronto office building it needs to sell to fund
overdue debt obligations.
Problems in raising funds from Exchange Tower, which houses O&amp;Y's head
office and the Toronto Stock Exchange, mirror a nervousness in financial
markets this week over O&amp;Y's inability to meet payments on its CDollars 20bn
(Pounds 9.7bn) debt.
Share prices of Canadian banks with a large exposure to O&amp;Y, as well as
Trizec, the property developer in which O&amp;Y has a 35 per cent interest, fell
to their lowest in a year in Toronto yesterday.
In addition, an O&amp;Y spokesman confirmed the company had failed to make
interest payments on a USDollars 800m (Pounds 458.3m) Eurobond secured by
one of the buildings in Manhattan's World Financial Centre. Last week, O&amp;Y
failed to make a principal payment on a CDollars 450m loan to finance
construction of Toronto's 68-storey Scotia Plaza.
A Toronto property financier said yesterday O&amp;Y has been involved in 'a fair
bit of activity' to line up a Canadian or foreign buyer for Exchange Tower.
O&amp;Y has been trying to sell Exchange Tower to raise funds to redeem a
CDollars 300m commercial paper programme secured by the building. About
CDollars 150m to CDollars 200m of the paper is still outstanding. No
payments have been made in recent weeks.
The company last week redeemed principal plus accrued interest on a second
CP programme following the receipt of funds from the sale of its controlling
interest in Interprovincial PipeLine of Calgary.
Among the options for Exchange Tower are a takeover by some O&amp;Y bank lenders
until another buyer can be found, and a sale-leaseback arrangement under
which O&amp;Y would regain ownership once its financial condition improves.
The search for a buyer is complicated by the steep fall in Toronto property
prices in the past two years. One property analyst said any pension fund or
bank which bought Exchange Tower at a depressed price faced having to write
down the value of its other property holdings.
He said only a handful of Canadian institutions had the resources to buy
Exchange Tower, while foreign investors were more interested in cheaper
buildings in US cities such as Houston and Dallas.
Bramalea issue, Page 26
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
