<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / PLO crisis talks as Arafat is reported missing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the Palestine Liberation Organisation called crisis talks last
night after an aircraft carrying Mr Yassir Arafat, the PLO's veteran leader,
was reported missing over the Libyan desert.
The aircraft, flying Mr Arafat from Sudan, disappeared from radar screens
during bad weather, according to the Libyan newsagency Jana.
Leaders of Mr Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction of the PLO held emergency
talks at their headquarters in Tunis to assess the implications. Although Mr
Arafat is unpredictable and elusive, PLO leaders were seriously concerned at
the lengthy loss of contact.
There was no immediate suggestion that the PLO leader had fallen victim to
an attack.
Libya's newsagency said Mr Arafat's aircraft disappeared about 70 miles from
the village of Sarra in the country's south-eastern desert. It vanished from
radar screens at 8.45 pm local time. Libyan radio quoted civil aviation
officials as saying that Al Kofra airport in Tripoli lost contact with the
aircraft due to 'bad weather conditions'.
The Libyans called for help from the International Red Cross, civil aviation
organisations and bodies operating international satellites and weather
stations.
A sandstorm, common for this time of the year in the desert regions of the
Middle East, was reported in the area where Mr Arafat's aircraft
disappeared.
Mr Arafat, who has been the PLO chairman since 1969, has survived a number
of attempts by the Israelis and others to eliminate him. At this stage, PLO
officials are not talking about foul play, but nor are they ruling out the
possibility of some interference with the PLO chairman's aircraft.
In Tunis, Mr Arafat's colleagues, used to his sudden disappearances and
reappearances, were at first sceptical of reports that his aircraft might
have gone down, but as the evening wore on without news of his whereabouts
their alarm increased.
The PLO leader was reported to be travelling with his usual complement of
bodyguards, secretaries and personal assistants. It was not clear whether
his new wife, Suha, was also on board, but she has travelled with him
constantly in recent months.
Among Fatah faction chiefs meeting in Tunis to discuss the latest apparent
twist in the PLO's fortunes were Mahmoud Abbas and Farouk Khaddoumi, along
with the PLO ambassador in Tunis, Hakem Belawi.
Mr Abbas, whose nom de guerre is Abu Mazen and who is regarded as a
moderate, has been spoken of as a possible successor in the event that
anything happened to Mr Arafat, who was 62 last August.
In Tunis, a PLO official said it was premature to speculate about a
successor.
</TEXT>
