FT  08 APR 92 / Clinton wins comfortably in critical New York primary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNOR Bill Clinton of Arkansas won a critical victory in New York's
Democratic primary early today, fending off a fierce challenge from Mr Jerry
Brown, his rival for the party's presidential nomination.
Early returns and exit polls showed Mr Clinton winning the New York primary
by a comfortable margin - although with much less than an outright majority
 -and also winning a sizeable victory in the much smaller Kansas primary.
The Wisconsin primary appeared to be much closer, although preliminary
estimates gave Mr Clinton the edge there too.
In the Republican primaries, President George Bush faced no contest in New
York, where Mr Patrick Buchanan, his right-wing challenger, was excluded
from the ballot paper, and won comfortably in Kansas and Wisconsin.
The campaign in New York had been brutally fought. Tabloid newspapers
attacked Governor Clinton's character with a savagery compounded by New
York's traditional prejudice against southerners, before turning their wrath
on Mr Brown, former governor of California.
After the Illinois and Michigan primaries on March 17, Governor Clinton had
appeared assured of a smooth ride towards winning the Democratic nomination
at the party convention in July.
But Mr Paul Tsongas's decision to suspend his candidacy threw Mr Clinton
into a duel with Mr Brown, whose slash-and-burn campaigning style was
fuelled by a victory in Connecticut's primary two weeks ago.
Despite suspending his campaign, Mr Tsongas attracted a sizeable vote in New
York and last night was considering whether to revive his candidacy.
The swirling fortunes of the campaign - and especially Governor Clinton's
travails over whether and where he smoked marijuana, and whether he dodged
the Vietnam war draft - have encouraged Washington pundits and Democratic
party officials to discuss scenarios for introducing another candidate, such
as Senator Lloyd Bentsen of Texas or Senator Al Gore of Tennessee. But these
wishful scenarios are sketched by the same people who drew up the party
rules that make a late candidacy all but impossible.
Even before yesterday's primaries, Mr Clinton had won 1,082 of the 4,288
delegates who will attend the party nominating convention in New York, far
ahead of Mr Brown's 166 delegates. The Arkansas governor seemed set to add
substantially to his total after yesterday's voting, in which another 362
delegates were at stake.
In Wisconsin, voters' favour had swung back and forth between the two
candidates, but neither man found much time to campaign in the state.
In Kansas, with 36 delegates at stake, Governor Clinton was the only
candidate to campaign.
</TEXT>
