<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / Labour plans new regime for auditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR intends to remove the accountancy institutes' self-regulatory powers
over auditors if it comes to power, it emerged yesterday.
In an apparent toughening of her previous position, Ms Marjorie Mowlam,
Labour's voice on City affairs, said Labour planned to transfer auditing
regulation to an independent body. 'We think the case is very strong for
independence,' she said.
The accountancy institutes for England and Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland
and the Irish Republic have been responsible for monitoring and regulating
nearly 10,000 accountants who are registered as auditors since the system
was set up by the Department of Trade and Industry last year.
Ms Mowlam's statement corroborates a document circulated to prospective
parliamentary candidates by her office some months ago which included a
proposal to regulate auditors independently of the professional institutes.
She said there was a common perception that the institutes were not
independent but acted more as trade associations. 'I don't believe their
track record suggests the kind of independence we would like to see,' she
said.
She added that she would not take any action until the end of this year,
when the first annual report on audit regulation will be submitted to the
DTI by the institutes.
One possible body to take over the regulatory function is the Accounting
Standards Board, but Ms Mowlam cautioned that it also required greater
openness in decision-making and wider representation on its board. The
Standards Board is funded and staffed by accountants.
News of the proposals came as a surprise to the professional institutes
yesterday. They maintain that self-regulation by accountants is the most
effective way to police auditors.
Mr Andrew Colquhoun, of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England
and Wales, said: 'We need a chance to demonstrate that the new regulation
system is working before anyone pulls up the plant by the roots.'
Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the Bank of England, last night called
for greater involvement by investors, brokers and analysts in the work of
the Accounting Standards Board and the Auditing Practices Board to help
raise the standards of corporate reporting.
Recent company failures had highlighted weaknesses in company accounts but
the accounts should not be 'the beginning and end of assessing a company's
position,' he said.
