FT  08 APR 92 / O&amp;Y keen to meet Tube line payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK, the property developer, is seeking a new timescale on
payments to secure an extension to the Jubilee underground line.
O&amp;Y is apparently committed to paying its full contribution to the project
and its legal representatives have been meeting London Transport in the hope
of reaching an agreement.
O&amp;Y was expected to pay the first instalment of Pounds 40m on March 31 but
was unable to do so. However, the Department of Transport has said that if
the agreement with O&amp;Y is not concluded before tomorrow's election, the
first payment will fall due on the day the agreement is signed.
Both O&amp;Y and London Transport are understood to have reluctantly concluded
that the future of the extension will have to await the outcome of the
election.
Much will depend on O&amp;Y's debt talks with banks, due on Monday.
London Transport would like O&amp;Y to stick as closely as possible to its
original timescale but it is thought that the developer favours a more
flexible approach.
London Transport said last night: 'We are anxious to start this project as
soon as possible but we cannot get the Secretary of State for Transport's
approval until we have sorted out the funding.'
Under proposals put to the department in 1989, O&amp;Y agreed to contribute
Pounds 400m towards the Pounds 1.3bn project.
A second instalment of O&amp;Y's contribution was scheduled for the end of March
1993, with the balance of Pounds 300m expected after completion of the
extension in 1996.
It is unclear whether a new timescale would delay the start of the project
or would put pressure on the incoming government to increase its
contribution at an earlier stage.
The developer believes Labour has given conflicting signals. Ms Joan Ruddock
has stated her support for the proposals but Mr John Prescott, the party's
transport spokesman, has warned that the project was 'going to be thrown
into the hands of the public sector'.
