FT  08 APR 92 / SE will start service to aid small stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STOCK Exchange is to introduce a special service to try to improve
dealing in 120 small stocks which are difficult to trade or illiquid in the
Official List and Unlisted Securities Market.
The exchange is starting a company bulletin-board service from April 27
which will run on Topic, its electronic information system. Information
about the companies will be provided, including details of the last 10
trades, the name of the company's corporate broker and current indicative
and firm market orders.
It will provide a more formal role for corporate brokers, who will be
responsible for providing information and easing trading in the stocks. In
the same way as an accredited dealer, corporate brokers will use best
endeavours to match and execute business. Members receiving buy or sell
instructions will first have to take account of any outstanding orders
displayed on the service if the same or a better price is available.
The changes follow criticism from investors and professionals about poor
liquidity in smaller stocks, and concern that information on potential
buyers and sellers is difficult to find.
Although liquidity of some tightly held shares will not be improved, the
exchange hopes the new service will make dealing in smaller companies more
efficient.
</TEXT>
