FT  08 APR 92 / Lloyd's confirms block on payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF London confirmed yesterday that it would act to block payments
from the Pounds 116m Outhwaite settlement to Names with outstanding
liabilities from their underwriting accounts.
Two legal advisers to Lloyd's suggested that the recoveries on behalf of
Names - the individuals whose assets underwrite the insurance business -
could be dealt with in accordance with its premium trust deed.
The deed will allow members' agents to retain any money from the settlement
to each Name up to the amount of any liabilities they have from membership
of underwriting syndicates.
The decision comes after talks started last Friday with representatives of
the 987 Names, who were members of the Outhwaite 316/661 syndicate in 1982,
and were due to benefit from the out-of-court settlement announced in
February.
Mr Peter Nutting, the businessman who negotiated the settlement, said he was
'absolutely furious' with the Lloyd's decision.
He said preparations had been made for payment of the money to Names this
week, and some were away on holiday without any knowledge that Lloyd's might
try to prevent payments being made.
The Names are seeking to avoid payment of claims this year and believe
evidence presented to the commercial court last week alleging irregularities
in the management of Gooda Walker syndicates has strengthened their case.
Mr David Coleridge, chairman of Lloyd's, said he considered the decision was
'entirely fair' to other Names who had met their own obligations and had to
contribute to central funds to meet others' liabilities.
It was unclear last night how many Names or how much of the settlement would
be affected by the decision.
</TEXT>
