<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / Iraq bows to demolition of nuclear facilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, Middle East Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ yesterday told United Nations inspectors that it would accede to their
demand to destroy buildings and equipment at the al-Atheer complex near
Baghdad - which UN experts say was central to Iraq's nuclear weapons
programme.
Mr Dimitri Perricos, who arrived in Baghdad with other International Atomic
Energy Agency experts only yesterday, said the Iraqi government had said
'they have agreed to all proposals and decisions of the agency regarding the
destruction of specified buildings in the al-Atheer site'.
Mr Perricos said he will lead his team to al-Atheer today to begin work on
the demolition. His inspectors are also set to visit 16 other sites said to
be related to Iraq's nuclear weapons programme.
Iraq's early decision not to resist the team's call to destroy parts of the
al-Atheer site is the clearest demonstration yet of Baghdad's improved
co-operation with UN inspectors charged with identifying and eliminating its
nuclear and weapons programmes.
</TEXT>
