<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / Volatile Fujimori's step back is a lonely one: The air of a
return to the bad old days in much of Latin America is more apparent than
real
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE dissolution of Peru's congress by President Alberto Fujimori, two months
after a failed military coup in Venezuela, has re-awakened images of Latin
America's autocratic past.
The Peruvian president's apparent extra-constitutional act also cast a pall
over the general air of optimism surrounding the annual meeting of the
Inter-American Development Bank in Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic.
The meeting yesterday celebrated an important debt breakthrough for
Argentina, the region's third-largest debtor after Brazil and Mexico, but
was left pondering the problems for democracy in the region created by the
economic reform movements that have swept the continent.
However, the air of a return to the bad old days is more apparent than real.
Latin America, unlike in the 1970s, is overwhelmingly a democratic
continent. The Rio Group of the 11 main Latin American governments joined
the widespread unequivocal international condemnation of Mr Fujimori's move.
'It's become very hard to argue in Latin America that you are taking
extra-constitutional action for a good cause,' said one official in Santo
Domingo.
There is a significant similarity between Peru and Venezuela - in all South
America they have perhaps the most underdeveloped political systems. One
academic in Washington last week described Venezuela as 'a city state with
an oil well'. The very idea of the nation is very weak in Peru.
However, an unravelling of the events in Peru and Venezuela, where a high
level of anxiety continues about further military challenges to the
government of President Carlos Andres Perez, shows important differences.
The Venezuelan coup attempt was triggered in large part by special factors
in the military largely unrelated to the government's economic programme
supported by the International Monetary Fund.
Events may yet derail the programme, but there appears to be a strong
realisation that if there were compromises to satisfy perceived political
pressure, there would be costs to other parts of society.
In Peru on the other hand, if Mr Fujimori's statements are to be believed,
the actions of this elected leader were taken to defend and deepen his
economic programme. The condemnation of his move externally contrasts
strongly with the apparently favourable reaction inside the country.
Nonetheless, Mr Fujimori's attempt to deepen economic reform may well be
frustrated by the suspension of aid and other financial and technical
assistance from important donors, in particular the US and Japan. Unless he
moves quickly to restore constitutional order, Peru risks becoming once more
as isolated internationally as it was under the populist government of
President Alan Garcia.
In this respect, the international community can have a significant
influence. Peru is heavily dependent on newly re-established financial flows
from the international community and the threat of effective sanctions could
have a significant impact.
This may provide some comfort to governments all over a continent that has
been wringing its hands over the inability to restore Haiti's short-lived
democracy.
This sense of helplessness had been reinforced by the hypothetical
difficulties which many saw in putting international pressure on a military
government in Venezuela. Since Venezuela is the second-largest supplier of
oil to the US and is the US's second-largest market in Latin America,
sanctions against it would have a far greater economic cost to Washington
than the action taken against an economically-backward Haiti.
In short, unless Mr Fujimori's action was meant either to pre-empt the army
or to be short-lived, he may have miscalculated. He has a reputation as a
lonely and volatile man: outbursts at the recent Latin American drugs summit
in San Antonio, Texas, surprised the other leaders present.
'Fujimori is no Machiavelli,' said one Peruvian in Santo Domingo yesterday.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
