FT  08 APR 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADING in the derivatives market continued to be dominated by hedging as
traders tried to second guess the outcome of tomorrow's election, writes
Joel Kibazo.
In stock index futures, the June contract on the FTSE was traded at a
healthy premium of 25 at the beginning of the session. But an early rise was
cut short by sellers, mostly independent traders as the large institutions
once again remained on the sidelines and June soon fell back to 2,422.
A brief rally, as several US houses went bargain hunting, was cut short by a
poor Wall Street opening.
Further falls were recorded towards the close as sizeable selling in the
traded options was hedged in the futures market.
June closed at 2,428, down 14 on the previous session and around two points
above its estimated fair value premium to cash of 22. Turnover reached 6,590
contracts.
In trade options, turnover returned to a more modest 24,466, down from
29,698 on Monday. Strong hedging business caused the FTSE option's daily
total to rise to 12,028 contracts. Among the stock options, Midland Bank led
the way with a day's total of 1,433 lots, followed by GEC at 1,135 lots.
