<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / UK impact on EC social policy 'limited'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S attempt to impose Thatcherite employment policies on the European
Community in 1986 was never expected to achieve more than short-term
political success and the government knew that the Brussels bureaucracy
would block it, according to an independent research body.
The unpublished assessment of the impact on EC social policy of the UK's
presidency of the Community in 1986 implies that its action programme for
employment growth created a backlash and led indirectly to the European
Social Charter, which the Conservative government has opposed.
The report was written by the National Institute for Economic and Social
Research for the Department of Employment. The UK is due to assume the
presidency of the Community again in July this year.
The case was seen as a textbook example of how the European Commission
neutralises proposals it opposes.
UK-style flexibility and deregulation of the labour market, was hailed by Mr
Kenneth Clarke, then paymaster-general and now education secretary, as 'a
milestone in tackling the problem of Europe's 16m jobless'. Eighteen months
after its adoption it was virtually forgotten, according to the assessment.
The UK programme was a short-term political success because all EC
social-affairs ministers were seen to back UK domestic policy, the institute
says.
The initiative by the government put unemployment high on the EC agenda and
showed a workable alternative to the European Commission's approach.
Yet the programme did not achieve its aim of changing the course of EC
social policy. Department of Employment officials failed to lobby hard for
Commission action after the programme was adopted. They knew any attempt to
oppose Commission policies would fail, the report concludes.
</TEXT>
