FT  08 APR 92 / Nissan will invest Pounds 20m in car R&amp;D
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN, the Japanese carmaker, is to invest Pounds 20m to expand its vehicle
design and development facilities in the UK, the company announced
yesterday. That will bring its total investment in design and development
operations in Europe to Pounds 64m.
Mr Yutaka Kume, Nissan's president, said the company also hoped to expand
production capacity in the UK to 400,000 cars a year by the end of the
1990s.
Officially Nissan has disclosed plans to date only for raising UK car
capacity to 300,000 a year by 1993.
Mr Kume said the company hoped to raise capacity to 400,000 a year without a
third model range. It is investing more than Pounds 900m at its Sunderland
car plant, where production begins this summer of the Micra small car in
addition to the existing Primera.
Nissan, the leading Japanese vehicle maker in Europe, is moving fast to
expand its European operations to stay ahead of its domestic rivals, chiefly
Toyota, the biggest Japanese carmaker, which starts car production in the UK
this year.
Mr Kume said the company was increasing investment at the Nissan European
Technology Centre at Cranfield, Bedfordshire, to Pounds 46m. The first stage
of the operation was officially opened yesterday.
In total, Nissan is investing Pounds 64m in its European design and
development operations, with Pounds 5m spent at Sunderland on a vehicle
proving ground and Pounds 13m invested at NETC Brussels.
NETC now employs 360 people in the UK. That will rise to 385 by next year.
Mr Kume said the expansion at Cranfield would allow vehicle prototype
development and assembly work to be moved from Japan to the UK. Engines and
chassis component assembly and testing would also move to the UK.
The NETC will be able to build and test prototype vehicles for Europe and to
test and refine engines for European-built vehicles.
Controversially, Mr Kume claimed that Nissan had become 'a fully integrated
European manufacturer designing, producing and selling vehicles in Europe
for European customers'. Nissan now has design and development centres in
the US and in Europe as well as the main facilities in Japan.
The expansion at Cranfield includes a road simulator and full climatic test
chamber with vehicle endurance testing. It is also building a soundproof
chamber for dynamic testing of vehicles at speeds up to 155 mph.
</TEXT>
