<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 92 / Investors switch into sterling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPPORT from Japanese and UK institutional investors buoyed the pound
yesterday as financial markets began to take a more sanguine view of the
repercussions if there is a change in the British government.
Investors switched money into sterling on calculations that a Labour
administration or a hung parliament was unlikely to lead to large-scale
selling of the pound.
As a result, sterling gained half a pfennig in London to close at DM2.8425.
Government gilt-edged securities gained about half a point, while on the
London stock market the FT-SE 100 Index of leading shares rose 3.3 to
2,404.2, continuing Monday's steady performance after a 65-point fall last
week.
Over the past few days, markets have taken heart from repeated assertions
from Labour that it would keep sterling within its existing band in the
European exchange rate mechanism.
That has calmed investors, who last week worried that an incoming Labour
administration would trigger a run on the pound. In such an event, the new
government might be forced to increase interest rates, holding back faint
stirrings of economic recovery.
Yesterday's events indicate that many investors have come to terms with a
Labour-led coalition or a Labour victory after tomorrow's general election.
Mr Bill Simpson, an economist in Barclays Bank's foreign exchange division,
said the buying pressure for sterling was due to fund managers 'appreciating
that the room for further downward movement in sterling is limited and that
there is plenty of upside potential'.
Currencies, Page 31 London stocks, Page 40
</TEXT>
