<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 92 / Survey of The Computer Industry (10): User-friendly systems
 -Pen-Based Computing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMPUTER keyboard is widely accepted to be, at best, an awkward
interface between man and machine.
Apple's success with the Macintosh, Microsoft's with its Windows icon-based
operating environment, and the proliferation of pointing devices - such as
the mouse - all appear to reflect the desire for a more intuitive interface.
The best hopes for developing a truly 'natural' interface probably lie in
either voice activated or pen-based computing (or a combination of both). Of
the two, pen computing is more developed with a handful of commercial
products already in the market and predictions from some manufacturers and
industry analysts that it will be 'the next personal computer boom
business'.
Portable computers, including hand-held units, are expected to be the main
PC growth market through the middle of the 1990s and BIS Strategic
Decisions, the market research company, predicts the market for pen-based
computer systems will be worth Dollars 1.5bn by 1995.
Among the first full function machines to reach the market are those from
manufacturers such as Grid, part of Tandy's Victor Technologies unit, AT&amp;T's
NCR subsidiary, Californian start-up Momenta, and Fujitsu's Poqet Computer.
These pen-based machines come in several guises. Momenta's new machine,
built around Intel's 80386sx chip and developed with Dollars 40m of venture
capital, is a hybrid since it comes with a wired copper-tipped electronic
'pen' and a small keyboard which its manufacturer claims makes it ideal for
applications such as taking notes at meetings, business planning or for
editing and correcting reports. The machine runs industry standard MsDos,
Momenta's own operating software, Momenta Software Environment (MSE), and
Microsoft's PenWindows.
However, most pen computers do not have keyboards - although some, including
Grid's new Gridpad SL, have ports at the back for a plug-in keyboard and VGA
monitor. Usually, however, they make do with LCD screens with digitiser pads
underneath that enable the screen to double as an electronic tablet or
slate, and a plastic stylus or 'pen' for 'writing'.
The pen is used to write free text, using one or more of the pen operating
systems, complete electronic forms by filling in boxes, or indicate sections
of a diagram on the computer screen - for example, marking the position of
damage on car bodywork.
One advantage claimed for pen systems is that they are simple to use and
will enable even the most keyboard-illiterate, from the chief executive to
the humblest blue-collar worker, to exploit computer technology.
The simplest pen-based systems are intended for applications where a paper
copy is required but where a printer would be cumbersome or too expensive.
One example of such a machine is the ScriptWriter, produced by Peripheral
Vision of the UK, which can be used for taking down an order, and leaving a
hard copy with the customer.
Because they are relatively simple, these electronic clipboards are
considerably less expensive than their more sophisticated counterparts.
Other machines are primarily intended for vertical applications, where
customised software enables engineers, market researchers, nurses or
surveyors, for example, to gather data.
In this role, the pen operates as a kind of glorified mouse, pointing to
items on the screen to select them. The pen can also be used to tick boxes
and to draw with the result saved as an image for later retrieval.
For example, insurance company assessors are using one application on the
Gridpad pen computer to calculate the cost of motor accident repairs by
displaying expanded vehicle diagrams on the screen.
By touching individual components on the screen with the pen, the machine
records the parts that need replacing.
The more sophisticated applications for pen computers depend on the
handwriting recognition software which comes with most of the latest
machines.
Using this software, pen-based systems can recognise and interpret letters
or numbers. However, the ability to use a pen computer like the traditional
notebook and pen is still some way off.
This is because you have to 'train' the software to interpret the quirks of
individual writing styles and even then most software will fail to correctly
identify as much as 20 per cent of the text.
What is more, most typists, even the two-fingered variety, can write more
quickly with a keyboard.
For these and other reasons some critics argue that the advantages of pen
computing are being overstated. Stephen Arnold, chairman and founder of
Softa, a UK-based independent systems consultancy, says that pen computing
appears to be a solution looking for an application.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-14233</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDHB2AAOFT</PROFILE>
